{"title_page": "The Perfection", "text_new": "Melanie Kelly {{Infobox film\n| name           = The Perfection\n| image          = The Perfection film poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Official poster\n| director       = [[Richard Shepard]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Bill Block]]\n* Stacey Reiss\n* Richard Shepard\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Richard Shepard\n* Eric Charmelo\n* Nicole Snyder\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Allison Williams (actress)|Allison Williams]]\n* [[Logan Browning]]\n* [[Steven Weber]]\n* [[Alaina Huffman]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Paul Haslinger]]\n| cinematography = Vanja \u010cernjul\n| editing        = David Dean\n| production companies         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Miramax]]\n* Capstone Film Group\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Netflix]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|9|20|[[Fantastic Fest]]|2019|5|24|United States}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fantasticfest.com/films/the-perfection/|title=The Perfection|website=[[Fantastic Fest]]|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''The Perfection''''' is a 2019 American [[psychological horror]] [[thriller film]] directed by [[Richard Shepard]], from a screenplay by Shepard, Nicole Snyder and Eric C. Charmelo. It stars [[Allison Williams (actress)|Allison Williams]], [[Logan Browning]], and [[Steven Weber]].\n\nIt had its world premiere at [[Fantastic Fest]] on September 20, 2018. It was released on May 24, 2019, by [[Netflix]].\n\n==Plot==\nCharlotte Willmore is a talented young [[cellist]] that was forced to leave Bachoff, a prestigious music school in [[Boston]], to care for her terminally ill mother. After her mother's death years later, Charlotte reaches out to Anton, the head of the academy, and travels to [[Shanghai]] to join Anton, his wife Paloma, and teachers Geoffrey and Theis in selecting a new student. Charlotte befriends Lizzie, Anton's star pupil who replaced Charlotte at Bachoff. After a night of clubbing, they return to Lizzie's hotel room and have sex.\n\nWhen Lizzie awakens with a [[hangover]], Charlotte offers her some [[ibuprofen]], which she takes with a shot of alcohol, and joins her on a trip through rural China. Boarding a bus after eating at a street food stall, Lizzie begins to feel progressively ill and takes more of Charlotte's ibuprofen. As her condition worsens, she throws up maggots and spirals into a panic, frightening the other passengers until the driver ejects her and Charlotte from the bus, stranding them in the countryside. Increasingly ill and paranoid, Lizzie sees bugs crawling inside her arm and eventually bursting out of her skin before Charlotte offers her a meat [[cleaver]], and Lizzie hacks off her infected right hand.\n\nIt is revealed that Charlotte drugged Lizzie with medication prescribed to Charlotte's late mother, which can induce hallucinations (especially when consumed with alcohol), stole the meat cleaver from the food stall, and manipulated Lizzie into cutting off her own hand.\n\nThree weeks later, Anton and Paloma give their new student from China, Zhang Li, a tour of Bachoff and the \"Chapel,\" an acoustically perfect room where the academy's best students perform. That night, Lizzie arrives unexpectedly, her right hand missing. She explains her recollection of events to Anton and Paloma, and that she was discovered unconscious on the side of the road with a makeshift [[tourniquet]] around her arm, keeping her alive. Lizzie is adamant that Charlotte orchestrated the incident out of jealousy. Anton, initially sympathetic, turns cold and informs Lizzie the next day that she must leave the academy. On her way out, she looks at the photos in the hall and smashes a framed picture of Charlotte.\n\nLizzie travels to [[Minneapolis]] to confront Charlotte in her home, having broken in and overpowers her with a taser before returning to Bachoff with Charlotte bound in the trunk of her car. When Charlotte awakens, she is confronted by Anton and reveals why she orchestrated Lizzie's dismemberment: the plot was spurred by Charlotte seeing a photo of Lizzie in a magazine with an eighth-note tattoo, a symbol for those indoctrinated into an elite group of students whom Anton and his peers [[Child sexual abuse|sexually abuse]] as part of a sex cult. Charlotte also bears the tattoo, having experienced years of rape and torture at the hands of Anton for failing to achieve musical \"Perfection,\" and planned Lizzie's amputation to save her from Bachoff, knowing that if she could no longer play the cello, Anton would have no use for Lizzie and discard her. Enraged, Anton brings Charlotte to the Chapel, where she is to perform for him, Paloma, Lizzie, Theis, Geoffrey, and an unwitting Zhang Li. She is seen sitting on the stage, chained by her ankles underneath a red dress, wearing red lipstick with her hair styled fancily. Anton states to Charlotte that if she plays a complicated piece without error, she will be free to leave. If she makes an error, Zhang Li will \"pay the price\" (presumably sexual abuse like what was inflicted on Charlotte). However, this is later revealed to be only a lie in order to throw Charlotte off her game.\n\nAfter the performance in which Charlotte erred, Anton, Paloma, and Zhang Li leave the Chapel, and Theis and Geoffrey bind Charlotte, preparing to [[Gang rape|gang-rape]] her. Lizzie threatens to rape Charlotte with her hand stump as revenge, but Theis and Geoffrey suddenly collapse and die. Lizzie and Charlotte kiss, and it is revealed the two conspired together, poisoning the men's drinks. Charlotte's plot to render Lizzie expendable to the academy resulted in Lizzie coming to her senses about Anton's [[brainwashing]], and together they plotted their revenge. Anton finds Paloma drugged and stabbed to death, and is confronted by Charlotte and Lizzie, armed with kitchen knives. They attack Anton, but he manages to wrest the knife from Charlotte, mutilating her arm before Lizzie knocks him unconscious.\n\nSome unspecified time later, Anton, his mouth and eyes sewn shut and limbs amputated, is forced to listen as Charlotte and Lizzie perform for him in the Chapel playing as one, each compensating for the other's missing hand.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Allison Williams (actress)|Allison Williams]] as Charlotte\n** Molly Grace as Young Charlotte\n* [[Logan Browning]] as Lizzie\n** Milah Thompson as Young Lizzie\n* [[Steven Weber (actor)|Steven Weber]] as Anton, the head of Bachoff Academy.\n* [[Alaina Huffman]] as Paloma, Anton's wife\n* Mark Kandborg as Theis\n* Graeme Duffy as Geoffrey\n* Eileen Tian as Zhang Li\n\n==Production==\nIn September 2017, it was announced [[Miramax]] would produce and finance the film, with [[Richard Shepard]], directing from a screenplay by himself, Nicole Snyder and Eric Charmelo, with [[Bill Block]] producing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/richard-shepard-the-perfection-miramax-films-the-matador-1202168969/|title=Miramax Buys Richard Shepard's Next Pic, 'The Perfection'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr|date=September 13, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> In October 2017, [[Allison Williams (actress)|Allison Williams]] joined the cast of the film, with Stacey Reiss serving as a producer on the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/allison-willliams-the-perfection-director-richard-shepard-horror-thriller-1202196357/|title=Allison Willliams Toplines Horror Thriller 'The Perfection' For Director Richard Shepard|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=October 27, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> In December 2017, [[Logan Browning]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/dear-white-people-logan-browning-allison-willliams-the-perfection-movie-1202229133/|title='Dear White People' Star Logan Browning Joins Allison Williams In 'The Perfection'|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere at [[Fantastic Fest]] on September 20, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/fantastic-fest-the-perfection-fugue-allison-williams-logan-browning-1202465624/|title=Fantastic Fest Adds Horror 'The Perfection' And 'Fugue' To Lineup|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Dino|last=Day-Ramos|date=September 17, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> Shortly after, [[Netflix]] acquired distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/netflix-buys-allison-williams-the-perfection-horror-miramax-movie-1202477386/|title=Allison Williams & Logan Browning Miramax Thriller 'The Perfection' Snapped Up By Netflix|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\nIt was released on May 24, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/12/30/2019-movies/|title=Here's every 2019 movie release date so far|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Katie|last=Hasty|date=December 30, 2018|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Expand section|date=September 2019}}\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 73% based on 88 reviews, with a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 6.55/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Led by a pair of compelling performances, ''The Perfection'' is a smart, gripping thriller that barbs its wild twists with cutting wit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_perfection/|title=The Perfection (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|accessdate=January 14, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], it has a weighted average score of 60 out of 100, based on 15 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-perfection|title=The Perfection Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=September 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe soundtrack for the film features multiple classical arrangements of [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]], [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]], and [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]], among others. It also features several non-classical tracks:\n\n* \"At Least I Still Have You\" by Rose Liu {{small|(Jason Zachary Parris, Lestley Renaldo Pierce, Rose Liu)}}\n* \"Ready or Not\" by [[Gizzle]] {{small|(Morgan Dorr, Timothy Healy, Glenda Proby)}}\n* \"Let's Make This a Moment to Remember\" by [[Chromatics (band)|Chromatics]] {{small|([[Johnny Jewel]])}}\n* \"It's On\" by Deuce Mobb {{small|(Jonathan Pakfar)}}\n* \"[[Petals (Hole song)|Petals]]\" by Chromatics {{small|([[Courtney Love]], [[Eric Erlandson]], [[Billy Corgan]])}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.netflix.com/title/80211638}}\n* {{IMDB title|7772580}}\n\n{{Richard Shepard}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perfection}}\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2018 horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s feminist films]]\n[[Category:2010s horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American feminist films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:American nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:American psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about child sexual abuse]]\n[[Category:Films about classical music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Films about cults]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Bill Block]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Paul Haslinger]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[